WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.280
So I appreciate the bit of history, because this talk is going to start with a story,

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:16.000
going all the way back to the year 2012.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:20.440
It was a time when I was a graduate student, I was programming a lot, and like a lot of

00:00:20.440 --> 00:00:23.959
people that program, I spent a lot of time on Stack Overflow.

00:00:23.959 --> 00:00:30.840
So there was a time that I ran into a question on Stack Overflow that hadn't been answered.

00:00:30.840 --> 00:00:34.759
It was a Python question, and I realized that I was able to answer it.

00:00:34.759 --> 00:00:37.279
So that was the first question answered on Stack Overflow.

00:00:37.279 --> 00:00:42.119
And I found in the years afterwards, I was doing my PhD work, I was writing some papers,

00:00:42.119 --> 00:00:46.900
and I was teaching, but I was also answering some questions on Stack Overflow, and I discovered

00:00:46.900 --> 00:00:51.480
a couple years later that one answer I left turned out to have a rather large impact on

00:00:51.480 --> 00:00:52.480
my life.

00:00:52.840 --> 00:01:00.040
So I answered about, let me see, 450 Python questions and 450 R questions, and one question

00:01:00.040 --> 00:01:04.440
about statistics, which was, what is the intuition behind the beta distribution?

00:01:04.440 --> 00:01:10.680
This is a question I saw, and I realized I had been given an answer to this individually

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:14.360
in a couple of courses that I taught and people that I talked to, and this was a chance to

00:01:14.360 --> 00:01:15.680
make it public.

00:01:15.680 --> 00:01:23.680
So I wrote an answer in response about comparing the beta distribution in baseball statistics.

00:01:23.680 --> 00:01:29.320
And I found out a couple years later, an engineer at Stack Overflow, the same company that I

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:33.199
was answering these questions on, discovered this question when he was working on improving

00:01:33.199 --> 00:01:34.879
AAB testing.

00:01:34.879 --> 00:01:39.400
So he ended up tweeting about that answer, and then he followed it shortly with, I don't

00:01:39.400 --> 00:01:42.919
know how much you're enjoying your PhD, but if you want an interview here, you can have

00:01:42.919 --> 00:01:46.320
one.

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:51.320
So a couple of weeks later, I interviewed with him, and that was my first data science

00:01:51.320 --> 00:01:53.519
job at Stack Overflow.

00:01:53.519 --> 00:01:58.599
I later learned the conversation that had gone on internally was the effect of, wow,

00:01:58.599 --> 00:02:01.519
what if we just hired that guy?

00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:06.120
This is what I'd call a freak accident.

00:02:06.120 --> 00:02:08.839
It's not something I would necessarily want to learn too much from.

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:14.039
I tell the full story in my blog post, One Year as a Data Scientist at Stack Overflow,

00:02:14.039 --> 00:02:18.320
but it is something that has profoundly affected my philosophy around public work.

00:02:18.320 --> 00:02:21.800
You see, when I was in graduate school, I thought of my goals like this.

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:25.759
I thought, well, I'm going to start with an idea, and that's just the beginning.

00:02:25.759 --> 00:02:28.279
Then I'm going to start working on it, get some preliminary results.

00:02:28.279 --> 00:02:31.960
Then I'm going to draft a manuscript, and it'll be most of the way there.

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:36.399
I'll complete the manuscript, and finally, one day, I'll have a valuable published paper.

00:02:37.399 --> 00:02:42.000
What I realized is I should have been thinking of my goals a little differently.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.399
Anything still on your computer is, to a first approximation, useless.

00:02:46.399 --> 00:02:47.839
It's not going to be shared.

00:02:47.839 --> 00:02:49.440
It's not going to be used by anyone else.

00:02:49.440 --> 00:02:53.600
When I look back at grad school, the things I did that ended up not being publicized,

00:02:53.600 --> 00:02:56.960
things that stayed on my computer, even I've forgotten them.

00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:00.919
If there is anything out in the world, it could be a published paper.

00:03:00.919 --> 00:03:04.199
It could be a product, like a web product.

00:03:04.199 --> 00:03:05.240
It could be a blog source.

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:09.119
It could be an open source contribution, or it could be as small as a tweet.

00:03:09.119 --> 00:03:13.600
All of those are way more valuable than anything that you didn't share.

00:03:13.600 --> 00:03:19.399
Fundamentally, I say it's a talk about public work, but it's really a talk about sharing.

00:03:19.399 --> 00:03:24.199
It's a talk about taking what we have and what we've gotten good at, taking our skills,

00:03:24.199 --> 00:03:31.199
and then sharing them with other people.

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:35.679
In particular, I'm going to walk through a few types of sharing that I think are incredibly

00:03:35.679 --> 00:03:40.240
effective, everywhere from blogging to writing a book.

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:45.320
I'm going to share my observation that no matter where you are in your career, these

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:49.800
are probably helpful, though each of these media probably becomes more helpful at later

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:51.399
stages of your career.

00:03:51.399 --> 00:03:56.639
So I'll start at areas where, even if you're an undergraduate student or an aspiring data

00:03:56.679 --> 00:04:01.679
scientist, you can still get into some of these media, like blogging and tweeting, and

00:04:01.679 --> 00:04:05.839
if you're someone with a lot of experience and expertise, some other technologies that

00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:10.279
you could use to share your work.

00:04:10.279 --> 00:04:13.440
So I'll give three reasons for spending time in public work, and they're going to keep

00:04:13.440 --> 00:04:15.600
reappearing throughout this talk.

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:19.820
The first is to advance your career, really to build a public portfolio of your work and

00:04:19.820 --> 00:04:22.399
let other people know about your skills.

00:04:22.399 --> 00:04:27.519
It led to a job for me, but it's also led to other opportunities and many other things

00:04:27.519 --> 00:04:31.359
that wouldn't have happened if I hadn't been sharing my work publicly.

00:04:31.359 --> 00:04:35.600
Certainly this keynote wouldn't have happened if I'd just been working without sharing anything

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:38.600
that I did online.

00:04:38.600 --> 00:04:40.399
Another is practicing good habits.

00:04:40.399 --> 00:04:45.200
I find that public work builds particular kinds of habits that you wouldn't build if

00:04:45.200 --> 00:04:49.359
you were, or at least more effective than you build them, working within one company,

00:04:49.359 --> 00:04:51.200
one team, or just on your own.

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:54.119
I'll go through a few examples.

00:04:54.119 --> 00:04:57.600
And finally, it helps you contribute to the community.

00:04:57.600 --> 00:05:01.640
There's selfless reasons that we want to share public work, to make sure that everything

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:04.760
that we build, other people can use.

00:05:04.760 --> 00:05:07.880
And a disclaimer.

00:05:07.880 --> 00:05:11.600
One is that, as I've already described in my own job story, a lot of this talk is what

00:05:11.600 --> 00:05:12.600
worked for me.

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:17.839
And that means we need an obligatory XKCD about survivorship bias.

00:05:17.839 --> 00:05:23.200
The fact is, we do need to observe that if I talk about just what had been working for

00:05:23.200 --> 00:05:27.559
me and my particular successes, maybe you don't see people that try that and it didn't

00:05:27.559 --> 00:05:29.320
work for them.

00:05:29.320 --> 00:05:32.760
I think this is very much worth keeping in mind and maybe taking it with a grain of salt,

00:05:32.760 --> 00:05:36.720
but I'd also say that I've seen a lot of people who have had a lot of success by sharing their

00:05:36.720 --> 00:05:39.000
work online.

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:43.480
And throughout this talk, I'm going to share particular examples of other people who, through

00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:49.880
blogging or tweeting or other types of public work, made a difference for themselves and

00:05:49.880 --> 00:05:52.239
their community.

00:05:52.239 --> 00:05:55.660
The second disclaimer is that this title is called The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Public

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:59.480
Work, not The Unreasonable Necessity of Public Work.

00:05:59.480 --> 00:06:03.000
There are other ways to succeed and there are other ways to have a really fulfilling

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:04.000
career.

00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:08.739
So, if you're someone who, some people just aren't going to have the time, maybe the ability

00:06:08.739 --> 00:06:13.040
or the interest in doing public work, but I'd like to convince as many people as possible

00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:16.119
that it might be interesting for you.

00:06:16.119 --> 00:06:21.119
So, I'm going to start with blogging.

00:06:21.119 --> 00:06:22.119
Why start a blog?

00:06:22.119 --> 00:06:25.359
Well, you can see a couple of reasons.

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:28.380
One of the most important is building a public portfolio.

00:06:28.380 --> 00:06:32.880
If you're someone early in your career who might start doing job interviews, a blog is

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:36.519
not just a great way to get employers to hear about you, it's a way to put your best foot

00:06:36.519 --> 00:06:37.519
forward.

00:06:37.519 --> 00:06:41.899
You can take whatever kinds of analyses you're most interested in doing, whatever skills

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:46.619
you're interested in showcasing, and put them online so that other people can use that to

00:06:46.619 --> 00:06:50.299
understand what you'd bring to a company.

00:06:50.299 --> 00:06:55.019
Another is that blogging is an incredibly effective way to practice writing, visualization,

00:06:55.019 --> 00:06:58.019
and other kinds of communication.

00:06:58.019 --> 00:07:02.239
In Hadley and Gary Grelin's book, R for Data Science, they talk about the importance of

00:07:02.239 --> 00:07:05.739
communication within the data science workflow.

00:07:05.739 --> 00:07:11.260
And it can often be hard to practice communication within a typical data science pattern.

00:07:11.619 --> 00:07:16.100
Sometimes it's hard to fit into a usual job.

00:07:16.100 --> 00:07:22.220
And blogging is all about what visualizations can I create, how can I structure my argument,

00:07:22.220 --> 00:07:26.500
how can I structure these points, and I've found that blogging has been one of the ways

00:07:26.500 --> 00:07:31.100
I've most improved my own writing skill.

00:07:31.100 --> 00:07:35.339
Third is that it's a way to teach or give advice in a way that scales, a way to change

00:07:35.339 --> 00:07:40.779
the community for the better by thousands of people at a time.

00:07:40.779 --> 00:07:45.220
So I've shared a thought that when you've written the same code three times, write a

00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:46.220
function.

00:07:46.220 --> 00:07:49.459
When you've given the same in-person advice three times, write a blog post.

00:07:49.459 --> 00:07:52.940
So the reasons for writing a blog post are similar for the reasons we'd write a functioning

00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:56.160
code, to avoid constant reuse.

00:07:56.160 --> 00:07:59.779
How often do you find yourself in a conversation, maybe at this conference, where you say to

00:07:59.779 --> 00:08:03.820
someone, oh, I have very strong opinions on that, let me try and walk you through them.

00:08:03.820 --> 00:08:07.260
And you meet someone else, and you walk them through those opinions as well.

00:08:07.739 --> 00:08:11.739
If you have a blog post, that's the opportunity for thousands or tens of thousands of people

00:08:11.739 --> 00:08:12.739
to read that opinion.

00:08:12.739 --> 00:08:17.059
And any time in the future you might want to change someone's mind, you can point them

00:08:17.059 --> 00:08:20.179
towards that.

00:08:20.179 --> 00:08:21.980
So how do you start a blog?

00:08:21.980 --> 00:08:27.739
There's the extraordinary blogdown package by Yihui Hsieh, as well as Amber Thomas and

00:08:27.739 --> 00:08:32.979
Allison Hill, who wrote the blogdown book, about creating websites with R Markdown.

00:08:32.979 --> 00:08:38.700
So if you've used R Markdown for creating reports, you can now use one R Markdown file

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:40.700
for each post in a blog.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:44.780
There's a really fantastic guide towards starting your own, and it's one that lets you integrate

00:08:44.780 --> 00:08:51.580
R, turn from R directly to code, results, and figures in your blog posts.

00:08:51.580 --> 00:08:57.419
I give a lot more advice in terms of how you can start a blog in Naturally, my blog post,

00:08:57.419 --> 00:09:01.739
advice to aspiring data scientists, start a blog, which I'm now pointing all of you

00:09:01.739 --> 00:09:06.659
towards and thereby proving my point.

00:09:06.659 --> 00:09:10.979
One of the points that I make in this blog post is that it can be very difficult to,

00:09:10.979 --> 00:09:14.700
it can feel like you're screaming into the void when you first publish online if you

00:09:14.700 --> 00:09:17.619
don't already have people that are following you.

00:09:17.619 --> 00:09:22.020
So my recommendation is if you start a data-related blog, tweet me a link, and I'll tweet about

00:09:22.020 --> 00:09:23.940
your first post.

00:09:23.940 --> 00:09:28.700
In the year plus since I made that offer, I've had the real privilege to get to retweet

00:09:28.700 --> 00:09:32.739
and tweet about a lot of people's work, a lot of people from all over the spectrum of

00:09:32.739 --> 00:09:34.219
a data science career.

00:09:34.219 --> 00:09:38.739
I'll share a couple examples of those in a moment.

00:09:38.739 --> 00:09:43.460
So if you're wondering what could I blog about, the place I'd always start is analyzing a

00:09:43.460 --> 00:09:44.460
data set.

00:09:44.460 --> 00:09:48.099
I think this is the bread and butter of data science blogging, is I've opened, I've created

00:09:48.099 --> 00:09:51.299
a new post, I'm going to start with a data set, I'm going to share some things that I

00:09:51.299 --> 00:09:52.299
learned.

00:09:52.700 --> 00:09:57.900
And for that, I think one of the most remarkable projects that enables that is TidyTuesday,

00:09:57.900 --> 00:10:01.380
run by the RF for Data Science online learning community.

00:10:01.380 --> 00:10:08.820
So this, each week, TidyTuesday releases a new data set every Monday, and then on Tuesday,

00:10:08.820 --> 00:10:12.419
the community generally discusses it, shares the results.

00:10:12.419 --> 00:10:17.260
So a fantastic approach to starting a blog is go to TidyTuesday, find the latest data

00:10:17.260 --> 00:10:21.700
set, or even an older one that you're interested in, share what you can learn from it.

00:10:21.700 --> 00:10:26.179
I think there's a lot of data sets you can use, though, and I want to highlight an example

00:10:26.179 --> 00:10:27.900
of someone who did it to remarkable effect.

00:10:27.900 --> 00:10:31.979
One of the people who shared their blog post with me was Jeff Kao, who was at the time

00:10:31.979 --> 00:10:36.260
an aspiring data scientist at the Metis boot camp.

00:10:36.260 --> 00:10:41.299
And he wrote an article discovering that more than a million net neutrality comments were

00:10:41.299 --> 00:10:42.700
likely faked.

00:10:42.700 --> 00:10:47.780
He used natural language processing to discover enough repetition in these comments to show

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:49.820
they were created by bots.

00:10:49.820 --> 00:10:56.299
And that actually got national news coverage and a lot of really notable attention.

00:10:56.299 --> 00:11:00.580
So one good place for looking for analyzing data might be current events that you're interested

00:11:00.580 --> 00:11:05.140
in and have a data-driven perspective to add.

00:11:05.140 --> 00:11:09.099
Another really good place to look for blog entries is if you're an academic, for every

00:11:09.099 --> 00:11:11.460
paper, turning it into a blog post.

00:11:12.219 --> 00:11:17.380
This is great advice from Philip Guo, where he shares that everything after his Ph.D.,

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:22.859
he's taken each of the papers, turned it into a blog post, and encourages students to do

00:11:22.859 --> 00:11:29.619
the same, because 10 to 100 more people will read blog posts than read a published paper.

00:11:29.619 --> 00:11:35.419
So peer-reviewed papers are a very important part of the public work ecosystem, but they're

00:11:35.419 --> 00:11:40.140
very well complemented by blog posts.

00:11:40.140 --> 00:11:44.859
Another great thing to do in a blog post is to teach a concept.

00:11:44.859 --> 00:11:49.859
So Mohamed was an aspiring data scientist who shared this post with me, and it was a

00:11:49.859 --> 00:11:53.219
really excellent look through some topics that he'd been learning about performance

00:11:53.219 --> 00:11:55.619
metrics for machine learning.

00:11:55.619 --> 00:12:00.380
So as he was learning these concepts, as he was taking classes and mastering these skills,

00:12:00.380 --> 00:12:04.179
he was also publishing this work online.

00:12:04.179 --> 00:12:07.580
When I talk to people that are taking data camp courses and are learning to become data

00:12:07.580 --> 00:12:11.940
scientists and they're asking me what's next, that's almost always my advice, to try creating

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:16.460
blog posts where they share what they've learned.

00:12:16.460 --> 00:12:18.619
Here's another fantastic example of teaching a concept.

00:12:18.619 --> 00:12:24.340
This is a blog post by Heather and Jacqueline Nolis about creating APIs in R.

00:12:24.340 --> 00:12:28.739
So this is the kind of tutorial where you include code, sometimes backing it up with

00:12:28.739 --> 00:12:34.340
some open source work, and therefore enable lots of people to be able to take this same

00:12:34.340 --> 00:12:35.340
approach.

00:12:36.099 --> 00:12:41.460
If you want to see loads of examples of people, everywhere from aspiring data scientists to

00:12:41.460 --> 00:12:46.099
experts, who ask me to tweet about their blog posts, you can check out the data blog hashtag

00:12:46.099 --> 00:12:47.099
on Twitter.

00:12:47.099 --> 00:12:51.299
Like I said, it's been really inspiring.

00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:55.140
Speaking of Twitter, the next kind of medium that I would recommend sharing your work in

00:12:55.140 --> 00:12:57.159
is Twitter.

00:12:57.159 --> 00:13:01.700
Who here has a Twitter account, let's say an active Twitter account?

00:13:01.700 --> 00:13:02.700
That's what I like to see.

00:13:02.700 --> 00:13:04.299
I think probably at least half.

00:13:04.299 --> 00:13:06.940
It's really exciting.

00:13:06.940 --> 00:13:11.099
Twitter is a short-form medium, that means it's not necessarily where you'd publish your

00:13:11.099 --> 00:13:15.820
work in the first place, but it's an amazing place to promote and discuss your work.

00:13:15.820 --> 00:13:20.820
So each time I come out with a blog post, I generally share it on Twitter, along with

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:23.260
a graph from it, and point people towards it.

00:13:23.260 --> 00:13:30.179
It's a good way to start discussion, get some comments, get some other opinions.

00:13:30.179 --> 00:13:31.659
But it doesn't have to be your own work.

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:35.299
It's also a fantastic way to promote the work of others.

00:13:35.299 --> 00:13:39.460
So Mara Averick, this is a really fantastic example from Mara Averick, where in December,

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:45.099
she decided to run a dev advent calendar, where every day she highlighted another data

00:13:45.099 --> 00:13:46.859
scientist and some of their work.

00:13:46.859 --> 00:13:53.299
So this was a fantastic way to use this platform of sharing to better strengthen the community

00:13:53.299 --> 00:13:54.900
and promote some people.

00:13:54.900 --> 00:13:59.539
So Mara is certainly, if you follow one person in the Twitter-R world, you can certainly

00:13:59.539 --> 00:14:02.219
follow her.

00:14:02.219 --> 00:14:05.659
It's also an amazing place to analyze datasets with the community.

00:14:05.659 --> 00:14:08.460
So I already mentioned the TidyTuesday project.

00:14:08.460 --> 00:14:13.539
Once people have finished analyzing a week's dataset, they can take that dataset, publish

00:14:13.539 --> 00:14:18.140
it, and discuss it, and share it on Twitter, and there are a few accounts, like the R4DS

00:14:18.140 --> 00:14:20.419
community account, that will generally retweet it.

00:14:20.419 --> 00:14:25.340
So if you're worried, I'm doing an analysis, is anyone going to see it, or is anyone going

00:14:25.340 --> 00:14:32.179
to think this is a topic worth analyzing, this is a really fantastic place to start.

00:14:32.179 --> 00:14:35.380
Another great example is sharing what you've learned at a conference.

00:14:35.380 --> 00:14:36.979
Who's been live-tweeting this conference?

00:14:36.979 --> 00:14:38.900
Solid, solid, yeah.

00:14:38.900 --> 00:14:45.500
So I'm going to share my favorite example of someone live-tweeting RStudioConf, who's

00:14:45.500 --> 00:14:52.219
Brooke Watson.

00:14:52.219 --> 00:14:56.940
Brooke's been doing these amazing posts where she takes notes, does a drawing of a speaker,

00:14:56.940 --> 00:14:58.919
and then shares it online.

00:14:58.919 --> 00:15:02.020
So this is definitely another fantastic person to follow.

00:15:02.020 --> 00:15:07.419
But there's lots of other creative ways to share the talks you're seeing, take a picture

00:15:07.419 --> 00:15:14.140
of a slide, share something you've learned, a particular funny joke, and somewhere else

00:15:14.140 --> 00:15:15.140
Twitter is really useful.

00:15:15.140 --> 00:15:18.340
I think it's especially amazing because we have to remember, not everyone is going to

00:15:18.340 --> 00:15:19.340
this conference.

00:15:19.340 --> 00:15:23.820
Even people that aren't even watching the stream of it, they still have the opportunity

00:15:23.820 --> 00:15:26.380
to learn something from it.

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:31.700
Finally, just because Twitter is a short-form medium doesn't mean you can't share work on

00:15:31.700 --> 00:15:32.700
it.

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:38.900
Here's a great example from Paige Bailey, who's at Google, who shares sets of code and

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:41.059
then visualizations that come from it.

00:15:41.059 --> 00:15:44.979
So this happened right after Twitter got 280 characters and this started being a little

00:15:44.979 --> 00:15:46.320
more possible.

00:15:46.320 --> 00:15:52.359
So it's a really good place to share an example of code, an R tip, maybe just a link to a

00:15:52.359 --> 00:15:56.840
really good data set, something that is useful in itself.

00:15:56.840 --> 00:16:02.640
As we'll see later, I think there's a lot of relationship between being able to communicate

00:16:02.640 --> 00:16:07.320
well in a short-form like this and being able to work in longer-form media.

00:16:07.320 --> 00:16:13.960
So in fact, one thing I discover is that sometimes if you have a really short post, even the

00:16:13.960 --> 00:16:17.719
fastest thing you do, sometimes, unfortunately, it can be much more popular than anything

00:16:17.719 --> 00:16:22.599
you put a lot more time into.

00:16:22.599 --> 00:16:23.799
So move on to the next area.

00:16:23.799 --> 00:16:27.080
This is something that once you've gotten a little bit of comfort, at least you have

00:16:27.080 --> 00:16:31.960
some comfort programming in R, you certainly don't have to be an expert.

00:16:31.960 --> 00:16:37.039
But once you're ready, an amazing point is to contribute to open source.

00:16:37.039 --> 00:16:42.039
So this is a slide from Mara Averick's talk, Contributing to Tidyverse Packages, that points

00:16:42.039 --> 00:16:47.320
out the motivation for open source is that it helps both yourself and the larger community.

00:16:47.320 --> 00:16:52.400
So when you find there's something you're working on, that's an amazing time, that you

00:16:52.400 --> 00:16:56.239
generally find useful, that's an amazing time to turn it open source.

00:16:56.239 --> 00:16:59.960
And the reason it's so helpful is that when you contribute to the community, you'll find

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:03.179
the community contributes back.

00:17:03.179 --> 00:17:06.880
So this was an example of some code that I wrote while I was in graduate school that

00:17:06.880 --> 00:17:11.319
I discovered that I often work with a linear model and I'd want to turn the coefficients

00:17:11.319 --> 00:17:13.880
into a data frame.

00:17:13.880 --> 00:17:17.000
So I had this code and I was finding it pretty useful for a few different problems I was

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:18.000
working on.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.540
I decided to release the open source package, Broom.

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:27.599
So I ended up promoting it on Twitter, as described before, it's a great way to share

00:17:27.599 --> 00:17:30.060
projects like this.

00:17:30.060 --> 00:17:35.619
And I found within the following years, it has gotten more than 200 pull requests.

00:17:35.619 --> 00:17:37.719
Other people improving this package.

00:17:38.119 --> 00:17:43.119
It's now grown, last year, in fact, it was taken over by Alex Hayes as a full-time maintainer.

00:17:43.119 --> 00:17:47.520
So this project has gotten so much bigger than I could have ever built, thanks to the

00:17:47.520 --> 00:17:53.160
fact that I was able to share it online.

00:17:53.160 --> 00:17:55.839
This kind of contribution can start just with a pull request.

00:17:55.839 --> 00:18:00.560
So here's a great article from Nick Crane on 10 Steps to Becoming a Tidyverse Contributor.

00:18:00.560 --> 00:18:07.560
So these are examples of how you can go into Tidyverse packages, discover some issues that

00:18:07.560 --> 00:18:09.439
you need resolving, and help out.

00:18:09.439 --> 00:18:13.520
It could be a bug fix, it could be a new feature, it could be as simple as a typo, but it's

00:18:13.520 --> 00:18:16.079
a great way to start working in open source.

00:18:16.079 --> 00:18:21.400
I think a particularly good initiative done by some Tidyverse packages, including Alex

00:18:21.400 --> 00:18:25.640
Hayes on the Broom package, is to create a list of beginner-friendly issues.

00:18:25.640 --> 00:18:29.920
These are issues that we would say, if you're just starting on GitHub, try going to this

00:18:29.920 --> 00:18:34.119
list, finding one that you can approach, and work your way up from there.

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:39.160
If you're somewhat more comfortable, it's a great time to create a package.

00:18:39.160 --> 00:18:41.719
Who here has created an R package?

00:18:41.719 --> 00:18:42.880
Nice.

00:18:42.880 --> 00:18:45.160
Who's published it on GitHub?

00:18:45.160 --> 00:18:46.160
On CRAN?

00:18:46.160 --> 00:18:48.160
Still pretty fantastic.

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:49.160
Yeah.

00:18:49.160 --> 00:18:53.079
Creating a package is an amazing way to get a lot of people to use your code, but it's

00:18:53.079 --> 00:19:00.040
also a great way to practice skills in documentation, unit testing, and creating intuitive user

00:19:00.040 --> 00:19:01.040
interfaces.

00:19:01.479 --> 00:19:05.880
So you can have a lot of experience coding for yourself on your own projects, but you'll

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:10.319
still be missing the kinds of practice that open source provides when you're writing code

00:19:10.319 --> 00:19:13.040
design for other people.

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:17.719
So Hadley's book, R Packages, is a fantastic resource for learning all the way from creating

00:19:17.719 --> 00:19:25.640
the code to writing the tests and documentation and publishing on CRAN.

00:19:25.640 --> 00:19:30.400
Moving on to the next recommendation is to give talks.

00:19:30.760 --> 00:19:32.640
So why should you give a conference talk?

00:19:32.640 --> 00:19:37.400
Well, you're all listening to me now, aren't you?

00:19:37.400 --> 00:19:40.719
But seriously, consider all the amazing things we've learned at this conference.

00:19:40.719 --> 00:19:43.599
So the last two days, these are a few of the amazing talks I've been to.

00:19:43.599 --> 00:19:44.839
I learned a lot about Shiny.

00:19:44.839 --> 00:19:46.520
I learned a lot about teaching.

00:19:46.520 --> 00:19:47.520
I learned about ggAnimate.

00:19:47.520 --> 00:19:49.760
I learned about R and APIs.

00:19:49.760 --> 00:19:52.359
I learned about what we've been doing in the ACLU.

00:19:52.359 --> 00:19:57.439
And this kind of conference is an opportunity to share what you're working on.

00:19:57.439 --> 00:19:59.300
Conference isn't a tutorial.

00:19:59.300 --> 00:20:00.300
It's not a resource.

00:20:00.300 --> 00:20:04.500
It's not an opportunity to go in front of people and make sure you change everything

00:20:04.500 --> 00:20:05.500
about them.

00:20:05.500 --> 00:20:07.459
It's not a chance to take all your expertise and put it in.

00:20:07.459 --> 00:20:08.619
It's a sales pitch.

00:20:08.619 --> 00:20:15.680
It's an opportunity to convince people that something is worth looking into.

00:20:15.680 --> 00:20:20.020
Some great advice for giving a data science talk comes from my sister Emily's blog post,

00:20:20.020 --> 00:20:22.900
Giving Your First Data Science Talk.

00:20:22.900 --> 00:20:27.180
Some of the useful recommendations that she adds include that you should imagine giving

00:20:27.180 --> 00:20:31.219
the talk to yourself from three to six months ago.

00:20:31.219 --> 00:20:35.739
So if you're thinking, I don't have anything I'd want to talk about, think, what do I know

00:20:35.739 --> 00:20:38.459
that six months ago I wish I'd known?

00:20:38.459 --> 00:20:42.500
And then try turning that into a talk.

00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:45.219
Another important aspect is to practice giving the talk out loud.

00:20:45.219 --> 00:20:49.280
It's even better if you can practice giving it to other people, but even just giving it

00:20:49.280 --> 00:20:54.079
to yourself out loud lets you notice where transitions might be awkward.

00:20:54.079 --> 00:20:57.959
And finally, she recommends you should not rely on bullet points.

00:20:57.959 --> 00:20:58.959
Oops.

00:20:58.959 --> 00:21:00.959
Sorry, Emily.

00:21:00.959 --> 00:21:06.119
You might think talking's not for you.

00:21:06.119 --> 00:21:08.119
You might say, what if I'm an introvert?

00:21:08.119 --> 00:21:12.680
Well, there's some really useful advice that's here from Kevin Goldsmith, which is one of

00:21:12.680 --> 00:21:17.000
the reasons speaking at conferences is great is it makes networking a lot easier.

00:21:17.000 --> 00:21:19.920
People know who you are and have something to talk to you about.

00:21:19.920 --> 00:21:23.760
So recommendation for introverts is to try becoming speakers.

00:21:23.760 --> 00:21:24.760
I should know.

00:21:24.760 --> 00:21:27.640
I'm an introvert myself, and now I have something to talk to you all about.

00:21:27.640 --> 00:21:32.439
But if you're still nervous, Emily has some great advice.

00:21:32.439 --> 00:21:38.520
Just imagine that your audience uses p-values of 0.25 for significance.

00:21:38.520 --> 00:21:46.680
There are a lot of fantastic places that you can speak.

00:21:46.680 --> 00:21:48.540
Some of them include local meetups.

00:21:48.540 --> 00:21:51.040
So you can find those often on Meetup.

00:21:51.040 --> 00:21:54.859
The R Ladies organization is a global organization that promotes gender diversity within the

00:21:54.859 --> 00:21:57.959
R community and has meetups all around the world.

00:21:57.959 --> 00:22:06.199
And here's a list of more than 350 R conferences and meetings in all kinds of countries that's

00:22:06.199 --> 00:22:07.199
really worth examining.

00:22:07.199 --> 00:22:12.880
So you can find a local meetup and give a talk there, but you can also give a talk at

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:14.599
a larger conference like this one.

00:22:14.599 --> 00:22:19.040
Often, it's a chance to reach a larger audience and also a chance to network with the larger

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:20.540
R community.

00:22:20.540 --> 00:22:24.140
When I've given talks at conferences like these, it's been really fantastic to meet

00:22:24.140 --> 00:22:27.819
people that are working on similar problems and are interested in talking to me about

00:22:27.819 --> 00:22:30.140
them.

00:22:30.140 --> 00:22:36.780
Finally, just because you're giving a talk doesn't necessarily qualify as public work

00:22:36.780 --> 00:22:39.180
unless there's a permanent artifact.

00:22:39.180 --> 00:22:43.140
This is something to really avoid, is that if you give a talk, you feel like you've got

00:22:43.140 --> 00:22:46.760
it out there into the world, but you never share it online.

00:22:46.760 --> 00:22:48.699
That makes it fundamentally ephemeral.

00:22:48.699 --> 00:22:50.780
You want to make sure you publish your slides.

00:22:50.780 --> 00:22:52.219
You can find this talk at this link.

00:22:52.219 --> 00:22:55.739
I'll be sharing it on Twitter afterwards as well.

00:22:55.739 --> 00:23:00.300
And Carl Broman's been doing a great service during this conference of keeping a list of

00:23:00.300 --> 00:23:04.140
links to slides from the conference on GitHub.

00:23:04.140 --> 00:23:09.099
So as people are giving their talks, or afterwards if you missed a talk or if you wanted to review

00:23:09.099 --> 00:23:14.219
something or visit a link from a talk or go into a little deeper, these slides are a really

00:23:14.219 --> 00:23:18.380
critical resource.

00:23:18.380 --> 00:23:23.339
This next media of public work is one that I only became familiar with and started really

00:23:23.339 --> 00:23:28.420
thinking about in the last few months, but it's one that I'm really excited about, particularly

00:23:28.420 --> 00:23:31.260
recording screencasts.

00:23:31.260 --> 00:23:38.060
This is an example of a screencast where I've been taking tidy Tuesday data sets each week

00:23:38.060 --> 00:23:43.900
and opening them without ever having looked at the data before, going into them, exploring

00:23:43.900 --> 00:23:49.540
it, making graphs, trying statistical models, thinking about my conclusions for about an

00:23:49.540 --> 00:23:53.780
hour without ever having seen the data before.

00:23:53.780 --> 00:23:59.300
So I found this a really exciting way to teach and to generally narrate my thought process

00:23:59.300 --> 00:24:05.339
and share it, particularly because it takes minimal preparation and a fixed time window.

00:24:05.339 --> 00:24:09.819
So if I'm at a point in my career where it can be difficult to schedule a lot of time

00:24:09.939 --> 00:24:16.619
to write, but I can always schedule an hour and a half to set up and record a screencast.

00:24:16.619 --> 00:24:22.500
It's also really great for letting you teach tricks that you wouldn't have thought of teaching.

00:24:22.500 --> 00:24:28.020
So for example, I use functions from the 4CATS package for working with factors a lot during

00:24:28.020 --> 00:24:33.719
these analyses, and I discovered that a lot of viewers, I hadn't necessarily thought,

00:24:33.719 --> 00:24:38.579
let me go teach the 4CATS package, but people watching them pick up on these tricks and

00:24:38.579 --> 00:24:44.939
these small things that they can do in R.

00:24:44.939 --> 00:24:51.140
Other things like the style of how I assign and name objects or tricks like manipulating

00:24:51.140 --> 00:24:54.660
variables within group by, again, these are things that I wouldn't write a blog post or

00:24:54.660 --> 00:24:55.660
a tweet about.

00:24:55.660 --> 00:25:00.979
I wouldn't think of making it a tip, but get to fit within a screencast.

00:25:00.979 --> 00:25:04.920
The limitation of screencast is that you need to be pretty capable and confident enough

00:25:04.920 --> 00:25:07.099
to improvise your way through a screencast.

00:25:07.099 --> 00:25:09.619
This isn't because it'll stop you from making mistakes.

00:25:09.619 --> 00:25:10.619
You will make mistakes.

00:25:10.619 --> 00:25:14.780
It's about being comfortable enough, embarrassing yourself sometimes.

00:25:14.780 --> 00:25:21.180
So for example, in one screencast, I find myself crashing RStudio four times in an hour.

00:25:21.180 --> 00:25:25.219
In another, I forgot about the lubricatesMdy function, I find myself rewriting it from

00:25:25.219 --> 00:25:27.699
scratch.

00:25:27.699 --> 00:25:33.300
And in probably the most embarrassing one, I started using ggAnimate and realized I didn't

00:25:33.300 --> 00:25:37.819
know how to use the new version, which since I was the one who published the initial version,

00:25:37.819 --> 00:25:44.380
is a little bit embarrassing.

00:25:44.380 --> 00:25:48.540
So this is something I don't know a lot of people who are doing screencasts.

00:25:48.540 --> 00:25:51.660
I've been encouraging some people I know to try out the format.

00:25:51.660 --> 00:25:55.500
One person who's doing a great job of it is Rachel Tapman from Kaggle, who doesn't just

00:25:55.500 --> 00:25:59.900
do screencasts, she does live coding on Twitch.

00:25:59.900 --> 00:26:03.739
So that's something I've thought about is, should I try doing the coding live?

00:26:03.739 --> 00:26:08.099
People can ask questions, can try and respond to feedback, they can point out the mdy function

00:26:08.099 --> 00:26:11.540
to me, and so on.

00:26:11.540 --> 00:26:19.380
So I'm really excited to see where screencasts might go in the future as a medium of teaching.

00:26:19.380 --> 00:26:24.260
Finally, I shared this advice before, when you've written the same code three times,

00:26:24.260 --> 00:26:25.260
write a function.

00:26:25.260 --> 00:26:28.979
When you've written the same in-person advice three times, write a blog post.

00:26:29.060 --> 00:26:35.300
Or, as Hadley advises, try writing a book.

00:26:35.300 --> 00:26:40.099
So writing a book is generally something that you'd want to be more advanced in a career.

00:26:40.099 --> 00:26:41.739
Who here has written a book?

00:26:41.739 --> 00:26:43.540
E-books count as long as you feel like they're finished.

00:26:43.540 --> 00:26:44.540
Who's written a book?

00:26:44.540 --> 00:26:54.619
Let's get a round of applause, I guess.

00:26:54.619 --> 00:26:59.699
Who thinks they plan to write a book sometime in their career?

00:26:59.699 --> 00:27:05.939
I'd encourage everyone to think about it seriously, because writing a book can seem somewhat intimidating,

00:27:05.939 --> 00:27:12.380
but it really fits as part of a continuum with a lot of these other media of communication.

00:27:12.380 --> 00:27:16.180
I think to write a book, the two things you need are a good amount to say, so you need

00:27:16.180 --> 00:27:19.939
to be a little farther in your career, enough to have a lot of advice you'd want to give

00:27:19.939 --> 00:27:24.380
on a technical or professional topic, and you'd have to have some practice in saying

00:27:24.380 --> 00:27:25.380
it.

00:27:25.380 --> 00:27:32.380
And that second part, the practice in communicating, is what all of this public work has been about.

00:27:32.380 --> 00:27:35.579
So we talked about short-form communication, like a tweet.

00:27:35.579 --> 00:27:40.260
So in a tweet, I might be able to do, this is a small bit of R code that's designed to

00:27:40.260 --> 00:27:46.660
demonstrate a concept of updating a beta distribution, and it's enough to fit in a tweet.

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:50.900
And then there's medium-form communication, and this can be everything from blog posts

00:27:50.900 --> 00:27:57.339
to package documentation, like vignettes, and building more practice doing this kind

00:27:57.339 --> 00:28:02.219
of writing helps one to get to long-form documentation.

00:28:02.219 --> 00:28:06.500
So in this case, I took a series of blog posts that I'd written, each teaching concepts around

00:28:06.500 --> 00:28:14.339
empirical Bayes estimation, and turned them into an ebook, Introduction to Empirical Bayes.

00:28:14.339 --> 00:28:19.979
So another great example of taking public work and building on it to create a book is

00:28:19.979 --> 00:28:21.380
from Julia Silgi.

00:28:21.380 --> 00:28:27.099
So Julia started by doing some blog posts about natural language processing, particularly

00:28:27.099 --> 00:28:30.619
sentiment analysis on Jane Austen novels.

00:28:30.619 --> 00:28:35.939
So she did some really fantastic blogging and was invited to our OpenSci hackathon,

00:28:35.939 --> 00:28:40.540
where she met me, and we together built the TidyText package.

00:28:40.540 --> 00:28:46.859
So she did blog posts, then maintained an open-source package.

00:28:46.859 --> 00:28:51.140
She followed this up with more blog posts that explained the philosophy of the package

00:28:51.140 --> 00:28:55.900
and how to use it, as well as a sequence of vignettes that go with the package that are

00:28:55.900 --> 00:28:59.420
medium-form documentation.

00:28:59.420 --> 00:29:05.140
And in 2017, we turned that into a book, Text Mining with R, available wherever books are

00:29:05.140 --> 00:29:07.180
sold as well as at that link.

00:29:07.859 --> 00:29:11.699
Do you notice how I plugged my two books, two slides in a row?

00:29:11.699 --> 00:29:15.819
Take notes, kids.

00:29:15.819 --> 00:29:16.819
How do you write a book?

00:29:16.819 --> 00:29:21.140
Well, luckily, Yihui is on the case, because there's the Bookdown package.

00:29:21.140 --> 00:29:27.180
So just as Blogdown allowed each RMD file to be one blog post, Bookdown has one RMD

00:29:27.180 --> 00:29:28.540
for each chapter.

00:29:28.540 --> 00:29:33.680
And Bookdown handles the enormous amount of formatting headaches and the nitty-gritty

00:29:33.680 --> 00:29:42.119
of references and indexes and all these problems, and it handles it for you so you can focus

00:29:42.119 --> 00:29:44.280
on the content and write something awesome.

00:29:44.280 --> 00:29:48.479
I find when I'm working with Bookdown, it feels more like I'm writing a sequence of

00:29:48.479 --> 00:29:54.359
blog posts than as if I have an enormous book that I have to contend with.

00:29:54.359 --> 00:30:03.599
In fact, all the books that I've described during this talk, all were developed in Bookdown.

00:30:03.599 --> 00:30:06.839
So why work publicly?

00:30:06.839 --> 00:30:11.680
Earlier I showed this slide, and I'm somewhat aggressive when I say work that's still on

00:30:11.680 --> 00:30:13.520
your computer is useless.

00:30:13.520 --> 00:30:14.520
Of course it's not useless.

00:30:14.520 --> 00:30:18.359
It could be something that you're working on within your company.

00:30:18.359 --> 00:30:21.119
It could be something that's helping you within your life.

00:30:21.119 --> 00:30:24.319
But why do I say it's so important to share your work?

00:30:24.319 --> 00:30:27.959
Well, imagine if nobody did.

00:30:27.959 --> 00:30:31.640
Throughout this entire series of slides, I've been highlighting a lot of people that have

00:30:31.640 --> 00:30:37.479
done great examples of public work, as well as people that have shared guidelines and

00:30:37.479 --> 00:30:41.560
resources and tutorials that will help other people do public work.

00:30:41.560 --> 00:30:46.359
And every time along the way, I've been putting the link on the bottom right so that afterwards

00:30:46.359 --> 00:30:49.680
you can go through and try some of these resources yourself.

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:52.319
Can you imagine if these hadn't been made public?

00:30:52.319 --> 00:30:57.119
I would have had to call my talk, The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Keeping Stuff on Your Computer.

00:30:57.119 --> 00:30:58.959
Later you would have watched it.

00:30:58.959 --> 00:31:02.719
It would have had slides like, my friend Bill did something cool, and he just told

00:31:02.719 --> 00:31:07.000
me about it at lunch last week and said, maybe I'll publish it someday.

00:31:07.000 --> 00:31:09.280
Think about those conversations you have.

00:31:09.280 --> 00:31:14.160
Think about when you talk to someone, you say, oh, I've got something really cool I've

00:31:14.160 --> 00:31:15.160
been working on.

00:31:15.160 --> 00:31:21.319
I've realized this interesting thing about this machine learning method, or I've found

00:31:21.319 --> 00:31:23.380
a really cool data set.

00:31:23.380 --> 00:31:26.119
If you never publish it, where does that end up?

00:31:26.280 --> 00:31:29.319
Can you say, my colleague Rachel made a great graph.

00:31:29.319 --> 00:31:31.199
She showed it to me on her computer.

00:31:31.199 --> 00:31:32.680
I wish you'd been there.

00:31:32.680 --> 00:31:37.680
They say that 80% of success is showing up.

00:31:37.680 --> 00:31:42.000
And similarly, I'd say to some extent, 80% of success within public work is getting your

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:43.079
work out there.

00:31:43.079 --> 00:31:48.280
So whatever you have, I really recommend thinking through these approaches and sharing your

00:31:48.280 --> 00:31:51.160
work.

00:31:51.160 --> 00:31:52.160
Thank you.

00:31:52.959 --> 00:32:04.880
Okay.

00:32:04.880 --> 00:32:10.520
I certainly hope that we have the fun throwable mics, maybe, out there.

00:32:10.520 --> 00:32:15.119
But we have definitely some time for some questions for David.

00:32:15.119 --> 00:32:20.300
And then, again, as promised, we'll have a break, and I'll tell you sometime when the

00:32:20.300 --> 00:32:21.800
panel will start.

00:32:21.939 --> 00:32:24.040
I see things being thrown.

00:32:24.040 --> 00:32:27.780
So that you know when to come in.

00:32:27.780 --> 00:32:28.780
All right.

00:32:28.780 --> 00:32:29.780
So I see a hand here.

00:32:29.780 --> 00:32:33.780
It's a little difficult with the lights and the fact that I can't see very well.

00:32:37.780 --> 00:32:38.780
Sorry.

00:32:40.780 --> 00:32:41.780
Oh, sure.

00:32:41.780 --> 00:32:42.780
This helps.

00:32:42.780 --> 00:32:43.780
So right in the middle.

00:32:43.780 --> 00:32:44.780
There.

00:32:44.780 --> 00:32:45.780
Yeah.

00:32:45.780 --> 00:32:46.780
Burgundy shirt.

00:32:47.780 --> 00:32:48.780
Ready?

00:32:52.780 --> 00:32:53.780
Hi.

00:32:53.780 --> 00:32:54.780
Hello.

00:32:54.780 --> 00:32:55.780
I was going to ask.

00:32:55.780 --> 00:32:58.479
One of the things that I think can be really hard if you're trying to write blog posts

00:32:58.479 --> 00:33:02.660
about data science, especially if you're sort of throwing it out into the void, is getting

00:33:02.660 --> 00:33:09.319
sort of, like, editing advice or maybe, like, any kind of feedback on your post before or

00:33:09.319 --> 00:33:11.660
when it's sort of, like, in draft form.

00:33:11.660 --> 00:33:14.660
Is there any kind of way in the art community we can sort of support that?

00:33:16.660 --> 00:33:18.660
I think that's a really interesting question.

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:22.520
I generally recommend when you're writing your first few posts and maybe you're not

00:33:22.520 --> 00:33:27.520
sure that you could use some feedback, still getting them out into the world.

00:33:27.520 --> 00:33:32.520
The art community is generally, I've found it very welcoming and is a good place where

00:33:32.520 --> 00:33:35.520
people can give some feedback.

00:33:35.520 --> 00:33:37.520
But I think that's the kind of initiative.

00:33:37.520 --> 00:33:40.520
I also think you can certainly go to your local community.

00:33:40.520 --> 00:33:46.520
So when I was in grad school, my lab mates and my advisor were fantastic resources.

00:33:47.380 --> 00:33:50.380
Your manager or colleagues are also great resources.

00:33:50.380 --> 00:33:54.380
I think it's the kind of thing that's probably worth formalizing in some kind of program.

00:33:54.380 --> 00:33:56.380
I don't know much about it.

00:33:56.380 --> 00:33:58.380
I don't know of anyone that's tried that.

00:33:58.380 --> 00:34:00.380
But, like, I don't know, Feedback Fridays.

00:34:00.380 --> 00:34:01.380
Feedback Fridays.

00:34:01.380 --> 00:34:02.380
You heard it here first.

00:34:04.380 --> 00:34:05.380
Let's go to Reina.

00:34:05.380 --> 00:34:06.380
Cool.

00:34:06.380 --> 00:34:07.380
Is this working?

00:34:07.380 --> 00:34:08.379
Awesome.

00:34:08.379 --> 00:34:09.379
Yeah.

00:34:09.379 --> 00:34:10.379
My name is Reina Harris.

00:34:10.379 --> 00:34:11.379
That was a beautiful talk.

00:34:11.379 --> 00:34:12.379
Thank you.

00:34:12.379 --> 00:34:15.379
The one thing you said, you need to have advice and experience to write a book.

00:34:16.239 --> 00:34:19.239
So what's maybe the harm in writing a book too soon?

00:34:21.239 --> 00:34:25.239
I don't think I've ever found a case where someone wrote a book too soon.

00:34:25.239 --> 00:34:31.239
One of the reasons I'm so encouraging throughout the book of doing public work is I think it's

00:34:31.239 --> 00:34:35.239
very rare that people fall on the side of publishing too often.

00:34:35.239 --> 00:34:38.239
Obviously, there are exceptions like data breaches and such.

00:34:38.239 --> 00:34:43.239
But I don't find that people, say, are writing too many blog posts analyzing data when they're

00:34:43.239 --> 00:34:44.239
too early in their career.

00:34:45.100 --> 00:34:46.100
That's certainly the other direction.

00:34:46.100 --> 00:34:51.100
I think the risk of writing a book too early is that you wouldn't have enough to fill it.

00:34:51.100 --> 00:34:56.100
I think the kinds of people I find, once you start, when you want to write a book, it's

00:34:56.100 --> 00:35:00.100
generally the kind of people that could fill up a university course with material.

00:35:00.100 --> 00:35:04.100
That might even be a little bit too much, but could certainly give a long talk, maybe

00:35:04.100 --> 00:35:08.100
a two-day workshop, and can think of enough facets of the problem where they'd want to

00:35:08.100 --> 00:35:09.100
give useful advice.

00:35:09.959 --> 00:35:14.959
I particularly think in this sense about both technical and professional help advice.

00:35:14.959 --> 00:35:20.959
I think if I imagine myself trying to write a book when I, let's say, just started grad

00:35:20.959 --> 00:35:23.959
school, I feel like I would run out of things to say.

00:35:26.959 --> 00:35:30.959
One thing I found is I keep running into people that have published books before they started

00:35:30.959 --> 00:35:32.959
their PhD or during their PhD.

00:35:32.959 --> 00:35:36.959
It's really not a thing that has a hard age or career cutoff.

00:35:37.820 --> 00:35:41.820
I really recommend thinking in terms, if you say write a lot of blog posts, how they can

00:35:41.820 --> 00:35:44.820
be linked together in the long form documentation.

00:35:44.820 --> 00:35:46.820
I feel like we've got one right around there.

00:35:46.820 --> 00:35:48.820
Thanks for the presentation.

00:35:48.820 --> 00:35:54.820
Do you have any opinion on the importance of updating older blog posts versus investing

00:35:54.820 --> 00:35:55.820
in writing new ones?

00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:57.820
I know it's not sexy, but...

00:35:57.820 --> 00:35:58.820
Yes.

00:35:58.820 --> 00:35:59.820
I'd say never do it.

00:35:59.820 --> 00:36:01.820
I'll tell you why you never update old blog posts.

00:36:01.820 --> 00:36:05.820
Because if you do, it stops you from writing future ones.

00:36:06.679 --> 00:36:09.679
It's not simply because you're spending time, you could be publishing the new ones.

00:36:09.679 --> 00:36:16.679
I would say it's because when you write a blog post, one of the amazing things about

00:36:16.679 --> 00:36:18.679
it is that it gets to be done.

00:36:18.679 --> 00:36:22.679
We call it the cult of done, is a popular description of this.

00:36:22.679 --> 00:36:27.679
So obviously you should fix errors or other problems in old blog posts.

00:36:27.679 --> 00:36:33.679
But if you find yourself treating a blog post as a resource that has to be maintained, for

00:36:34.540 --> 00:36:36.540
example, if I went back to my...

00:36:36.540 --> 00:36:38.540
I think I have a very old blog post that uses data.table.

00:36:38.540 --> 00:36:44.540
If I went back and used dplyr, if I went back and fixed the various things that have broken

00:36:44.540 --> 00:36:50.540
thanks to new dplyr releases, that would mean every new blog post that I wrote would become

00:36:50.540 --> 00:36:51.540
an obligation.

00:36:51.540 --> 00:36:54.540
And that would discourage me from publishing them in the first place.

00:36:54.540 --> 00:36:59.540
So it's a bit of an extreme answer, but I'd actually say I would not prioritize that very

00:37:00.399 --> 00:37:06.399
heavily, with clear exceptions such as if someone finds something truly wrong in it

00:37:06.399 --> 00:37:09.399
or dangerous or other things like that.

00:37:09.399 --> 00:37:11.399
I'd say put it out there and let it be done.

00:37:11.399 --> 00:37:13.399
Work on the next thing.

00:37:13.399 --> 00:37:14.399
I'm pretty...

00:37:14.399 --> 00:37:16.399
I think I see who has this microphone.

00:37:16.399 --> 00:37:19.399
Over here, on your left-hand side.

00:37:19.399 --> 00:37:21.399
Thanks, David.

00:37:21.399 --> 00:37:23.399
I have a really important question for you.

00:37:23.399 --> 00:37:27.399
Did I pay you to promote the two books of mine?

00:37:28.260 --> 00:37:30.260
Was that an option?

00:37:32.260 --> 00:37:34.260
Alright, the real question.

00:37:34.260 --> 00:37:41.260
So I actually have a problem with tweeting, which is discoverability.

00:37:41.260 --> 00:37:49.260
I mean, many times I see there are excellent tweets sharing excellent ideas, but I feel

00:37:49.260 --> 00:37:55.260
like if I miss such a tweet, I feel it's just gone forever.

00:37:56.120 --> 00:37:58.120
So do you think that is a problem?

00:37:58.120 --> 00:38:00.120
And if you do, how would you solve that?

00:38:00.120 --> 00:38:04.120
Yeah, I would say the advantages of Twitter are very ephemeral.

00:38:04.120 --> 00:38:08.120
It's very much, during this conference, see everything that's happening.

00:38:08.120 --> 00:38:14.120
It's not an ideal way to crystallize knowledge for future use, not the way a blog post or

00:38:14.120 --> 00:38:16.120
especially a book would be.

00:38:16.120 --> 00:38:22.120
Having said that, there are a few ways that it makes things permanent that I really enjoy.

00:38:22.979 --> 00:38:24.979
So if you haven't tried this, you should try it.

00:38:24.979 --> 00:38:28.979
I'm not going to do it on my computer, but you could go to Twitter and do from colon

00:38:28.979 --> 00:38:32.979
a username and search only within one person's tweets.

00:38:32.979 --> 00:38:37.979
So if you know, oh, I said something once, or Emily said something, or I want to find

00:38:37.979 --> 00:38:41.979
a tweet where Jenny shared this really good piece of advice, you can search just within

00:38:41.979 --> 00:38:43.979
one person's tweets.

00:38:43.979 --> 00:38:47.979
One way that I use that is for finding my own conference tweets.

00:38:48.840 --> 00:38:52.840
During a conference, I generally treat Twitter as a public diary.

00:38:52.840 --> 00:38:56.840
I'm not very good at note-taking, so instead I live-tweet each of the talks with what I

00:38:56.840 --> 00:39:01.840
find most important, and afterwards I can go back and discover the things that I wanted

00:39:01.840 --> 00:39:03.840
to share.

00:39:03.840 --> 00:39:09.840
So throughout this talk, I do include a few of my old tweets, and I did find them in this way.

00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:13.840
So I think we should take one more question, then we'll have our break in the panel.

00:39:13.840 --> 00:39:15.840
So have we already given out the mic?

00:39:16.699 --> 00:39:18.699
Yeah, can you all hear me?

00:39:18.699 --> 00:39:19.699
No?

00:39:19.699 --> 00:39:20.699
Yeah?

00:39:20.699 --> 00:39:24.699
So I think after hearing you talk, we all seem very motivated to write blog posts, but

00:39:24.699 --> 00:39:30.699
how would you recommend that people stay, like keep the momentum and continually publish

00:39:30.699 --> 00:39:34.699
blog posts, not just like after this conference right now, but maybe in like three months,

00:39:34.699 --> 00:39:37.699
six months, even a year?

00:39:37.699 --> 00:39:43.699
You know, when I started my blog, it was late 2014, and it was around the time also that

00:39:44.560 --> 00:39:48.560
I started the Broom package, and I waited a few months, and I wrote four blog posts

00:39:48.560 --> 00:39:52.560
because I knew that once the blog was up, I assumed I'd be out of ideas, and I could

00:39:52.560 --> 00:39:56.560
never blog again, so I wanted to have four saved up that I could publish.

00:39:56.560 --> 00:40:00.560
And every single time I've published in a blog post since then, I've thought, yep,

00:40:00.560 --> 00:40:02.560
this is the last one, I'm out of ideas.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:06.560
What I'd say is the best way to keep motivated is to start that feedback loop, is once you

00:40:06.560 --> 00:40:12.560
put ideas out in the world, you get feedback on them, you get people excited about them,

00:40:13.419 --> 00:40:18.419
you get compliments on them, sometimes you get recognized, and these are ways that build

00:40:18.419 --> 00:40:22.419
your own excitement and keep you motivated to keep doing work online.

00:40:22.419 --> 00:40:30.419
So I'd say there isn't a shortcut to starting and putting your work online.

